author: @markkennedy9767
text: I can see how objects and instances can be so confusing for people. First off, I understand why people find the self parameter confusing: it basically insists that when we send the object itself as an argument to the parameter self when we call the class for the first time that this object exists (which it doesn't because the instance hasn't been created from the class until we send the argument to self).   Apart from that, all the aliasing (not sure if that's the correct term) going on is confusing: so basically when we call the class to create the instance, we do this by sending arguments which are "aliased" with parameters (blackboxes) which carry the information about the arguments to the right side of any assignments in the body of the class, which are assigned to variables which are created from a parameter (self, which we are not free to make up) dotted with a name we are free to make up. Phew.

author: @Qelacien
text: What a great video, i have no words. Thank you Thank you Thank you!!! I just want to share 1 thing from goolge for those who might have some difficulties with the word instance.    *An instance, in object-oriented programming (OOP), is a specific realization of any object. An object may be varied in a number of ways. Each realized variation of that object is an instance. The creation of a realized instance is called instantiation.  Each time a program runs, it is an instance of that program. In languages that create objects from classes, an object is an instantiation of a class. That is, it is a member of a given class that has specified values rather than variables. In a non-programming context, you could think of "dog" as a class and your particular dog as an instance of that class.*

text: My notes: 1) attribute refers the member variables of a class, methods are operations/functions 2) instanciating an object is to create an instance of a class 3) self refers to the instance of an object  4) note that there's never "variable declaration" in python 5) self is not required as a first argument for every class method. But that means one may need to use static method , which is something useful for grouping functions related to a class but don't require knowing the state of the class. For static method declared inside a class, we still have function call like className.static_method()

author: @kodikodi7963
text: Great Video mate! Question? Just curious... In one of the videos I previously watch, they try to rename the attributes with a leading underscore.  like:      def __init__(self, first, last, pay):         self._first = first         self._last = last         self._pay = pay The video says to avoid name clash with the method of the same name, and we already have an attribute called "first" and we don't want to replace it.  There's a widely followed convention that the implementation details of an object, which are not intended for consumption or manipulation by clients of the object should be prefixed with an underscore.

author: @lavenarch9570
text: This video was extremely helpful  even 5 years later! I shared it with my SO who is learning python as well. Also, it was fun to extend capabilities of this class by adding a pin protected method to see an employee's salary     class Employee:     def __init__(self, first, last, pay, pin):          self.first = first         self.last = last         self.email = f'{first}.{last}@company.com'         self.pay = pay         self.pin = pin          def fullname(self):         return f'{self.first} {self.last}'        def salary(self):          passw = input('Please enter pin to see employee\'s salary:')         if passw == self.pin:             return self.pay         else:             print('Sorry, you have entered the wrong pin.')

author: @atlantic_love
text: This video really fails at the thing that almost all OOP videos fail at: TEACHING OBJECT ORIENTED DESIGN.  It's relatively simple to "make a class", or derive or extend one.  Now, sit down and design a class-driven program.  Much, much more difficult.  Until you can take a "use case" (description of what your program does and who the "actors" are in that program design and turn it into a model, all of these "make a class" videos are useless.  It's like a racer teaching a newbie "how to drive a car".  Does nothing in the grand scheme of things.

text: Continue at 9:00 ish  Maybe ask yourself, the thing Im about to program, is it a thing? Or a type of thing? If you are going to have a program that talks about a PS4, then eh. But if your talking about consoles AND PS4s, then you‚Äôre talking about a type of thing, and a thing, so perhaps you should use a class.   It seems that there are types of data, and functions (blocks of code) we can use on these specific types of data. It seems like both, types of data, and associated functions are chosen arbitrary, so we can make our own of both. We can make our own types of data (classes), and their corresponding functions (methods). author: @user-xc5xf8gp8n
text: Summary: Using classes help us to group data and functions in a logical way. Data and functions that are associated with a class are respectively called an attribute and method for the class. Classes are the blueprint of the instances, while instances are the specific case of an class.   To create attributes of a class, use the special init method. (Special methods are methods that require the double underscore, '__' besides it)   There are 2 ways to use a method. First is calling the method by 'first typing the class name, period, and typing the method name' in this case, we have to type in the 'self' argument manually. The second is using the '.method()' way after the name of the instance. In this case, the self argument is passed in automatically.

Because surname and name are NOT visible here         return '{}, {}'.format(self.last, self.first)      emp1 = Employee('Corey', 'Shafer', 50000) print("You can reach ",emp1.fullname(), "on ", emp1.email)  What my question is now : Is there a preferable way  for constructing the email attribute/(class variable) ?

author: @tauraamui
text: Object orientation isn't the utilisation of the class type of structure, it's a state orchestration concept in which you have compartmentalized object instances and they send messages to other instances, this is a way of attempting to prevent state being altered from within one object by another. OOP isn't just using classes to represent real life concepts, that's not what it is supposed to mean.

 map = {}         map ['gene'] = self.name         map['samples'] = sorted([self.samples[sample_key].format() for sample_key in self.samples], key=lambda sample: sample['sample'])         return map author: @12345charliebrown
text: just managed to get myself out of the OOP mindset after years of wasting my time with it, and I've gone back to procedural based coding. There are very few times where abstraction is used and when it is, I find the library written in OOP over complicated and over engineered. A warning to those starting out in Python or Programming in general, you'll find lots of tutorials based around OOP like this video. On the surface it makes sense and the logical thing to do is to wrap everything in a class but in real world coding it's a massive piiful. Take the OOP tutorials with a pinch of salt.   I'm not dissing Corey himself, I think his videos are very helpful and Ive have brushed up on some of my Python skills watching his videos but the Object Oriented Programming side is a waste. Most of you will never need to know what Abstraction and Polymorphism is or will ever have to use it. Imagine having to wade through 4 sub level classes to find that do_something() has no relation to that sub class and could quite easily have been made into a function. Check this video out https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o9pEzgHorH0

author: @tonyquigley6543
text: Hi Corey can i ask you a question, why does every single one of these Java or Python videos basically make nothing?  What i mean by that is, when people envision being a programmer, they imagine making their own program, with menus and buttons and shit to click on and fields to fill in and drop down menus etc, but literally every single Python or Java (or any language for that matter) just teaches you what a string is, what a short or long is, and how to assign a value to piece of data and to store it.  Like adding names and ages to an array etc. But it's all in the Python compiler (or Java) window, and it's boring as hell, how come not one person has come on here and gone "Hey, you see this cool little program i have here that you can launch fro your desktop, and it can search your computer for any files you want, you just select the dowon menus and this tab and that tab and blah blah". Do you get me? Because If i hear one more person say "the best way to learn is just to ignore the tutorials and just sit there and try to code".  But the problem is, thats impossible, as we're basically stuck, completely limited to that little Output window after you click the green arrow.   I mean, do people really consider the fact that they just spent 40 minutes going through a bunch of strings and ints and how to link them to values etc, all to press the green button to get an ourput underneath that says "Orange, 141, Orange and Green, Orange, Green and Purple, 2948, Your answer was correct, your answer was incorrect"   Do you get me? Im not gonna sit there after this 45 min lesson and think, "Ok thats awesome, now i can use the principle of this, and i can start to build my own little desktop application using the same resources as he was using, i can change certain things and instead of drop down boxes, i can have check boxes, and neat warning window that came up, i could totally customize that to do this and that".   What you've really shown us (an i promise I'm not directing this specifically at you man) is how to type in expressions and how to print them in a box underneath without any errors.  Man thats not programing or being creative, thats what everyon else did.  How are we supposed to take the knowlege you/they gave us from that "int myResource = 2 +3; " and go ahead and build a desktop application, that when you open it, it asks you for your phone number and password you use to log into your phone providers online text messaging service for you without you having to go to the website yourself etc...   Show me how to make an external program, with boxes, and windows and menus.   I love what you're doing, just please expand for us, we know all this small stuff., If you're to be more successful, we need to know how to ACTUALLY make a program, where to get external data and forms and boxes and windows etc. Not like i sais "myValueOne + myValueTwo = Result;" you know?   Again, I love you, but let's go man!!!

author: @ericorabello
text: I'm trying to figure out a way to create an object automatically using the info inserted by the user as class parameters. So I wrote a little program for practice. In this case, I used LIST.APPEND() to store the user info and then used the indexes to get the parameters. Is it a good way to do so? Would be glad if someone could point me how to make it better. Thanks! ------------------------------------------------------------- # This program asks the user for employees data and then prompts a summary  class Employee:     def __init__(self, first, last, pay):         self.first = first         self.last = last         self.pay = pay         self.email = first + "." + last + "@company.com'"      def summary(self):         return  f"{self.first} {self.last} - {self.email} - ${self.pay}.00"  tot_employees = 0 employees = [ ]  while True:     key = input("Add employee to database?\n[Y/N]")      if key in "Yy":         tot_employees += 1         first = str(input("First name: ")).capitalize()         last = str(input("Last name: ")).capitalize()         pay = int(input("Salary: "))         employees.append([first, last, pay])      # <-- STORING INSERTED INFO IN LIST         # Ex: employees = [["Erico", "Shimada", 30000], ["Test", "User", 90000], [...]]      elif key in "Nn":         print("... Program ended")         break     else:         print("Invalid option")  print(f"\nThe company has {tot_employees} employees:") employees.sort()  for i in range(0, len(employees)):     employees[i] = Employee(employees[i][0], employees[i][1], employees[i][2])     # employee[0] = Employee("Erico", "Shimada", 30000)     print(employees[i].summary()) --------------------------------------------------------------------------- Output: Add employee to database? [Y/N] y First name: erico Last name: shimada Salary: 30000  Add employee to database? [Y/N] y First name: test Last name: user Salary: 90000  Add employee to database? [Y/N] n ... Program ended  The company has 2 employees: Erico Shimada - Erico.Shimada@company.com - $30000.00 Test User - Test.User@company.com - $90000.00

author: @kdeuler
text: Corey, I have a basic newbie question on instantiation: What are the advantages, in the greater OOP programming environment, of instantiating a programmer-defined class more than once?  Say I have a "Movies" class. Each instance of the class is a list containing a movie title, and perhaps a sublist of actors in the movie. Let's say that I instantiated several movie objects. My question is, then what? What could I do with all these instances? I could print them out, and perhaps compare them in some ways. But how is instantiation in OOP better than manipulating a pointer in a database with functional programming. It seems to me that a program can really only deal with a set of movie information one at a time, so why fill up memory with objects?  Thanks in advance!   And as others have written, great series of lectures. So glad I found them. A comfortably fast pace. Thanks for the hard work.

text: I've been learning Python as my first language for a few months now, but I got stuck and couldnt' grasp the concept  of OOP via Python. I started leaning OOP through books in Ruby, and I felt like the way it is presented in Ruby is SO much easier to comprehend compared to Python. I guess there's a reason why OOP is usually introduced within the first three chapters of any Ruby textbook (forgiving syntax/true object oriented language) vice Python which teaches OOP in much much later chapters. At any rate, once I understood the basics of OOP in Ruby (took like 2-3days).. the transition to Python OOP was pretty easy.. It's essentialy all the same besides some terminology differences.  Great video and thanks :-)

author: @swallowedinthesea11
text: Thanks! I learned a lot, and the multiple comparisons greatly helped too. I created this using functions and then evolved it into a class.   class Measures:      def choice(self):         self.choice = int(input('Which choice? \n'))         if self.choice == 1:             self.feetToAcre()         elif self.choice == 2:             self.feetToInch()         elif self.choice == 3:             self.inchToFeet()         elif self.choice == 4:             self.area()         elif self.choice == 5:             self.feetToYard()         elif self.choice == 6:             self.yardToFeet()         elif self.choice == 7:             self.yardToInch()      def feetToAcre(self):         print('ACRE -> FEET')         self.acre = int(input('Enter acre: '))         self.acre *= 43560         print(self.acre, 'sq. ft.')      def feetToInch(self):         print('FT. -> INCH')         self.sqFt = int(input('Enter feet: '))         self.sqFt *= 12         print(self.sqFt, 'inches')      def inchToFeet(self):         print('INCH -> FEET')         self.inch = int(input('Enter inch: '))         self.feet = self.inch // 12         print(self.feet, 'feet')      def area(self):         print('AREA')         self.length = int(input('Enter length: '))         self.width = int(input('Enter width: '))         self.area = self.length * self.width         print(self.area, 'sq. ft.')      def feetToYard(self):         print('FEET -> YARD')         self.feet = int(input('Enter feet: '))         self.yard = self.feet / 3         print(self.yard, 'yards')      def yardToFeet(self):         print('YARD -> FEET')         self.yard = int(input('Enter yard: '))         self.feet = self.yard * 3         print(self.feet, 'feet')      def yardToInch(self):         print('YARD -> INCH')         self.yard = int(input('Enter yard: '))         self.inch = (self.yard * 3) * 12         print(self.inch, 'inches')  print("""\t\t\t\tWhich option?               1. Acre to feet              2. Feet to inch              3. Inch to feet              4. Area              5. Feet to yard              6. Yard to feet              7. Yard to inch""")  x = Measures() x.choice()
